DATA

I read in the 3 cleaned csv-files (cleaned in Open Refine on beforehand). One for each list. The last part colClasses = character is in order to read the data as characters and not as numbers, because otherwise the commas in the files are lost.

ghettoer <- read.csv(file = "data/Ghettoer_clean.csv", colClasses = "character")
hrdeghettoer <- read.csv(file = "data/Hrde_clean.csv", colClasses = "character")
udsatte <- read.csv(file = "data/Udsatte_clean.csv", colClasses = "character")

I wish to test, if the values in the dataframes are read as numbers, even though I specified it as characters. And they are!

ghettoer %>% 
    ggplot() + geom_bar(aes(x = Omrde, y = Etnicitet), stat = "identity", fill = "yellow")

DATA WRANGLING 1

I wish to have a dataframe with all the areas (vulnerable & ghettoes) in which it is possible to see how the area is categorized. Therefore, I merge the dataframes I add to the dataframe udsatte (vulnerable) the coloumn Etnicitet from the dataframe ghetto.

etnicitet <- ghettoer %>% 
    select(Omrde, Etnicitet)
samlet <- merge(x=udsatte, y=etnicitet, by = "Omrde", all.x = TRUE)

Now that I have a way to differentiate the ghettoes, I can use the mutate in combination with the if-else function to create a coloumn that adds the value ghetto, if the ethnicity is > 50, and vulnerable area if it is under.

samletkategoriseret <- mutate(samlet, Ghetto = ifelse(Etnicitet > 50, "''Ghetto''", "''Vulnerable Area''"))

It does not count in the NAs, so instead I add the value Vulnerable Area in this way:

samletkategoriseret$Ghetto[is.na(samletkategoriseret$Ghetto)] <- "''Vulnerable Area''"

I wish to further differentiate the ghettoes, so it shows which are hard ghettoes When I try to merge the tables (the last line, 77), only one of the hard ghettoes appear. I cannot figure out why? Therefore, I do not use the new dataframes in the following plots

HrdeGhettoer <- hrdeghettoer$Omrde
allareas <- samletkategoriseret %>%
    mutate(samletkategoriseret, Categorization = ifelse(samletkategoriseret$Omrde %in% HrdeGhettoer, "Hrd Ghetto", "Ikke"))
    
hrdeghettoer_2 <- hrdeghettoer %>% 
    mutate(Kategoriseret = "Hrd_Ghetto")

HRD <- hrdeghettoer_2 %>%

allcategorized <- merge(x=samletkategoriseret, y=HRD, by = "Omrde", all.x = TRUE)

Now I can start plotting. I wish to have a plot that shows the crime rates for each area and which clearly shows, if the area is defined as a ghetto or not. I do this by using an argument that picks color according to the value of the Ghetto coloumn. Furthermore, I add ad intercepting line to mark where the threshold value is for the areas to meet the criteria. I have used the following tutorial to receive help on customizing labels on the plot: http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/ggplot2-axis-ticks-a-guide-to-customize-tick-marks-and-labels

DATA WRANGLING 2

I wish to do an analysis to see how many areas that meet each of the 4 criteria.

First, I need to change the commas in the dataframes, so R can read it properly.

samletkategoriseret$Dmte <- gsub(",",".", c(samletkategoriseret$Dmte))
samletkategoriseret$Uddannelse <- gsub(",",".", c(samletkategoriseret$Uddannelse))
samletkategoriseret$Indkomst <- gsub(",",".", c(samletkategoriseret$Indkomst))
samletkategoriseret$Etnicitet <- gsub(",",".", c(samletkategoriseret$Etnicitet))
samletkategoriseret$Ledighed <- gsub(",",".", c(samletkategoriseret$Ledighed))

Second, I create an object for each criteria using the length argument to summarize the number of areas that meet each criteria.

n_dmte <- length(samletkategoriseret[samletkategoriseret$Dmte >=2.03, "Dmte"])
n_ledighed <- length(samletkategoriseret[samletkategoriseret$Ledighed > 40, "Ledighed"])
n_uddannelse <- length(samletkategoriseret[samletkategoriseret$Uddannelse > 60, "Uddannelse"])
n_indkomst <- length(samletkategoriseret[samletkategoriseret$Indkomst < 55, "Indkomst"])

I create a new dataframe that contains a coloumn with these lengths and a coloumn with the names of the criterias

n_alle <- c(n_dmte, n_ledighed, n_uddannelse, n_indkomst)
kriterier <- c("Crime Rate","Employment","Education","Income")

criteriacount <- data.frame(n_alle, kriterier)
